com.apriori.collections

Class TreiberStack<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<T>
      • com.apriori.collections.TreiberStack<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the type of values stored in the stack
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    SizedIterable<T>, Stack<T>, java.lang.Iterable<T>, java.util.Collection<T>

    public class TreiberStack<T>
extends java.util.AbstractCollection<T>
implements Stack<T>
    A thread-safe stack. New elements are CAS'ed onto the head of a linked list. Elements are removed similarly: CAS'ing their predecessor to point at their successor.

    This structure exposes the operations of a stack, and iteration yields the newest elements first. But it can be useful as a general-purpose thread-safe collection. For example, it can be used for waiter queues, where each element added is a parked thread.

    This structure is safe to use concurrently from multiple threads. Iterators will never throw ConcurrentModificationExceptions. However, a single iterator is not meant to be used by multiple concurrent threads and is thus not thread-safe. This collection supports all optional operations.

    Bulk operations are not atomic. So reads that execute concurrently with bulk operations may see partial results from the in-progress bulk operations.

    See Also:
    SimpleTreiberStack
